@startuml recall-consolidate-consolidation
' The handoff sequence: the index_builder snapshots Recall up to N,
' builds + commits the shard (consolidated_lsn = N), then runs a grace-bounded
' idempotent trim (to the 2nd-newest shard's watermark). Annotates the
' load-bearing commit-the-shard-BEFORE-trimming-Recall ordering and the grace
' buffer, and marks the crash-safe windows across the two-database seam (no
' distributed transaction): Recall rows in RB_RECALL_DSN, consolidated_lsn in
' the control-plane catalog.

title Consolidation handoff: build -> commit shard -> grace-bounded trim, crash-safe

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Helvetica
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam ArrowFontSize 11
skinparam NoteFontSize 10
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

queue "CONSOLIDATE\ntopic" as q
participant "index_builder\n(single replica,\nper-dataset advisory lock)" as builder
database "Recall\n(pgvector, RB_RECALL_DSN)" as recall
collections "Consolidate\n(object store: shard + sidecar)" as os
database "shard_catalog\n(control-plane PG,\nconsolidated_lsn)" as catalog

q -> builder : trigger\n(cap RB_RECALL_MAX_ROWS exceeded\nOR idle-tick sweep)
activate builder
builder -> builder : acquire per-dataset advisory lock\n(serialised vs any build/delete)

== Step 1: snapshot (single read txn) ==

builder -> recall : recall_snapshot_for_consolidation\n(tenant, dataset) up to max(lsn) = N\n(LIVE rows + tombstones)
activate recall
recall --> builder : snapshot of (W, N]
deactivate recall
note right of builder
  A write that lands AFTER this snapshot (lsn > N)
  stays in Recall -> still queryable via the union ->
  folded by the NEXT consolidation. Read-your-writes
  holds THROUGH a consolidation.
end note

== Step 2: build the shard ==

builder -> os : _add_to_index / fresh build;\n_write_shard + sidecar\napply tombstones (deleted=true -> _remove_ids,\ndropped from sidecar, never added)
note over builder, os #LightYellow
  CRASH-SAFE WINDOW A (before commit):
  shard may be half-written but NOT committed ->
  catalog still points at the old shard; Recall is
  still authoritative for (W, N]; consolidation retried.
  No loss, no duplicate.
end note

== Step 3: COMMIT the shard (BEFORE trimming Recall) ==

builder -> catalog : COMMIT shard_catalog row:\nconsolidated_lsn = N, build_type='consolidate';\nsupersede sweep (keep newest 2); evict superseded from cache
activate catalog
catalog --> builder : committed
deactivate catalog
note over builder, catalog #LightSalmon
  CRASH-SAFE WINDOW B (between commit and trim):
  shard committed (has (W, N]) but Recall not yet trimmed.
  Recall still holds rows with lsn <= consolidated_lsn -- the
  union HARMLESSLY excludes them (lsn > N is false). No loss
  (shard has them), no duplicate (union excludes Recall copy).
  Next consolidation GCs them. This ordering is load-bearing:
  NEVER trim before commit, or a crash leaves rows in NEITHER tier.
end note

== Step 4: grace-bounded idempotent trim (only after commit) ==

builder -> recall : recall_trim:\nDELETE WHERE lsn <= 2nd-newest shard's consolidated_lsn\n(grace_watermark = W, NOT the just-committed N)
activate recall
note right of recall #E9F7E9
  GRACE BUFFER: rows in (grace_W, N] are KEPT one extra
  generation, so an in-flight query that resolved an OLDER
  shard (wm <= W) still finds its Recall rows -- it uses the
  watermark of the shard it actually read. First-ever
  consolidation: its new shard is the only one ->
  grace_W = 0 -> trims nothing.
  Idempotent: DELETE WHERE lsn <= grace_W is re-runnable.
end note
recall --> builder : trimmed (idempotent)
deactivate recall

builder -> builder : release advisory lock
deactivate builder

@enduml
